On Frequency Estimation for Partially Observed Processes with Small Noise in Observations.

O.V. Chernoyarov Yu.A. Kutoyants Le Mans University, Le Mans, France,
Abstract

We consider the problem of frequency estimation of the periodic signal multiplied by a stationary Gaussian process (Ornstein-Uhlenbeck) and observed in the presence of the white Gaussian noise. We show the consistency and asymptotic normality of the maximum likelihood estimator in the asymptotics of small noise in observations. The model of observations is a linear nonhomogeneous partially observed system and the construction and study of the estimator is essentialy based on the asymptotics of the equations of Kalman-Bucy filtration.

MSC 2000 Classification: 62M02, 62G10, 62G20.


Key words: Partially observed linear system, frequency estimation of noise-type signals, small noise asymptotic.

1 Introduction

The problem of frequency estimation is of special interest in telecommunication theory. The shift of the frequency allows to estimate the speed of the object (Doppler effect). The estimation of the frequency of the Gaussian signals observed in the WGN like the studied in this work is of interest in statistical radio physics.

This is the second work devoted to the frequency estimation by the observations of partially observed linear nonhomogeneous system. In the first work we studied the properties of the maximum likelihood estimators (MLE) and Bayes estimators (BE) in the situation, where the noises in the state and observation equations tend to zero [2]. It was shown that these estimators are consistent and asymptotically normal. Here we study a slightly different model of observations, where the noise in the state equation does not tend to zero and we have asymptotics of small noise in the observations equation. The detailed study of dynamical systems with small perturbations (noise) can be found in [3]. The statistical problems for such models are presented in [12].

4 Discussions

The results on frequency estimation by the observations of stationary Gaussian process Ytsubscript𝑌𝑡Y_{t} satisfying linear equation in the presence of WGN are valid for much more general models of inhomogeneous processes Ytsubscript𝑌𝑡Y_{t} and (smooth) functions f​(ϑ,t)𝑓italic-ϑ𝑡f\left(\vartheta,t\right). We did not use the periodicity of f​(ϑ,t)=f​(ϑ​t)𝑓italic-ϑ𝑡𝑓italic-ϑ𝑡f\left(\vartheta,t\right)=f\left(\vartheta t\right) and the relation

limε→0∫0TM˙​(ϑ,t)2​dt=0subscript→𝜀0superscriptsubscript0𝑇˙𝑀superscriptitalic-ϑ𝑡2differential-d𝑡0\displaystyle\lim_{\varepsilon\rightarrow 0}\int_{0}^{T}\dot{M}\left(\vartheta,t\right)^{2}{\rm d}t=0

holds for inhomogeneous processes Ytsubscript𝑌𝑡Y_{t} too. Recall that we took this model of observations just for the comparison of the properties of estimators for different limits.

Recall that if the smooth signal f​(ϑ​t)𝑓italic-ϑ𝑡f\left(\vartheta t\right) is observed in the WGN (say, Yt≡1subscript𝑌𝑡1Y_{t}\equiv 1 in (2)) and T→∞→𝑇T\rightarrow\infty, then the rate of convergence of the MLE ϑ^Tsubscript^italic-ϑ𝑇\hat{\vartheta}_{T} is T3/2superscript𝑇32T^{3/2} [8]:

T3/2​(ϑ^T−ϑ)⟹𝒩​(0,I∗​(ϑ)−1)⟹superscript𝑇32subscript^italic-ϑ𝑇italic-ϑ𝒩0subscriptIsuperscriptitalic-ϑ1\displaystyle T^{3/2}\left(\hat{\vartheta}_{T}-\vartheta\right)\Longrightarrow{\cal N}\left(0,{\rm I}_{*}\left(\vartheta\right)^{-1}\right)

with some I∗​(ϑ)>0subscriptIitalic-ϑ0{\rm I}_{*}\left(\vartheta\right)>0. In the case σ=b=ε→0𝜎𝑏𝜀→0\sigma=b=\varepsilon\rightarrow 0 studied in [2] we have

ϑ^ε−ϑε⟹𝒩​(0,I​(ϑ)−1).⟹subscript^italic-ϑ𝜀italic-ϑ𝜀𝒩0Isuperscriptitalic-ϑ1\displaystyle\frac{\hat{\vartheta}_{\varepsilon}-\vartheta}{\varepsilon}\Longrightarrow{\cal N}\left(0,{\rm I}\left(\vartheta\right)^{-1}\right).

and the limit variance I​(ϑ)−1Isuperscriptitalic-ϑ1{\rm I}\left(\vartheta\right)^{-1} for large T𝑇T is of order T−3superscript𝑇3T^{-3}, i.e.; if we consider the second limit T→∞→𝑇T\rightarrow\infty, then the normalization formally can be written as follows

T3/2​(ϑ^ε−ϑ)ε⟹𝒩.⟹superscript𝑇32subscript^italic-ϑ𝜀italic-ϑ𝜀𝒩\displaystyle\frac{T^{3/2}\left(\hat{\vartheta}_{\varepsilon}-\vartheta\right)}{\varepsilon}\Longrightarrow{\cal N}.

In our case σ=ε→0𝜎𝜀→0\sigma=\varepsilon\rightarrow 0 and b>0𝑏0b>0 fixed we have

ϑ^ε−ϑε​b⟹𝒩​(0,I~​(ϑ)−1),⟹subscript^italic-ϑ𝜀italic-ϑ𝜀𝑏𝒩0~Isuperscriptitalic-ϑ1\displaystyle\frac{\hat{\vartheta}_{\varepsilon}-\vartheta}{\sqrt{\varepsilon\,b}}\Longrightarrow{\cal N}\left(0,\tilde{\rm I}\left(\vartheta\right)^{-1}\right),

where

I~​(ϑ)=∫0Tt2​f′​(ϑ​t)2​dt.~Iitalic-ϑsuperscriptsubscript0𝑇superscript𝑡2superscript𝑓′superscriptitalic-ϑ𝑡2differential-d𝑡\displaystyle\tilde{\rm I}\left(\vartheta\right)=\int_{0}^{T}t^{2}f^{\prime}\left(\vartheta t\right)^{2}{\rm d}t.

Therefore if b→0→𝑏0b\rightarrow 0 (second limit), then we can write formaly the normalization ε​b𝜀𝑏\sqrt{\varepsilon b}. If we consider now the third limit T→∞→𝑇T\rightarrow\infty, then we can wait that

T3/2​(ϑ^ε−ϑ)ε​b⟹𝒩.⟹superscript𝑇32subscript^italic-ϑ𝜀italic-ϑ𝜀𝑏𝒩\displaystyle\frac{T^{3/2}\left(\hat{\vartheta}_{\varepsilon}-\vartheta\right)}{\sqrt{\varepsilon\,b}}\Longrightarrow{\cal N}.

We have to note that the calculation of the MLE for the model of partially observed linear system is of extreme computational complexity because to calculate it we have to know the solutions of the filtration equations (2), (6) for all ϑ∈Θitalic-ϑΘ\vartheta\in\Theta. To realize an estimator asymptotically equivalent to the MLE and much more easy calculated we can use the Multi-step MLE approach developed in [14], [11]. In the case of periodic signal in WGN the similar One-step MLE approach was realized in [4]. The most interesting case of frequency estimation for the model of observation (2),(3) is T→∞→𝑇T\rightarrow\infty and it will be considered in our next work. For periodic diffusion processes the similar problems of frequency estimation were considered in [6], [7]
